00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:16.560
What's Eating Gilbert Grape.

00:01:16.560 --> 00:01:17.560
Let's roll the clip.

00:01:17.560 --> 00:01:18.560
[pause]

00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:19.560
[Applause]

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:20.560
&gt;&gt;Peter: Mm hmm.

00:01:20.560 --> 00:01:31.360
&gt;&gt;Claire: So to start us off, I was just curious
to hear

00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:33.780
about the process of adapting your novel to
the screen

00:01:33.780 --> 00:01:37.220
and what that was like, what that experience
was like.

00:01:37.220 --> 00:01:40.840
&gt;&gt;Peter: Well, Gilbert Grape, What's Eating
Gilbert Grape was my first novel

00:01:40.840 --> 00:01:49.050
and I had the opportunity to write the screenplay
but because I came from writing for the theater

00:01:49.050 --> 00:01:54.660
I liked writing dialog and I was working with
a great filmmaker,

00:01:54.660 --> 00:02:00.290
Lasse HallstrÃ¶m who's Swedish
and wasn't as interested in dialog

00:02:00.290 --> 00:02:07.730
because film is ultimately a visual storytelling
experience.

00:02:07.730 --> 00:02:10.990
So it was great, it was great.

00:02:10.990 --> 00:02:12.170
It was hard.

00:02:12.170 --> 00:02:16.570
I started writing and Johnny Depp was a big
fan of the novel

00:02:16.570 --> 00:02:20.790
and committed to do the film before the screenplay
was done,

00:02:20.790 --> 00:02:24.390
so we were in pre-production
and I'm still trying to figure out how to

00:02:24.390 --> 00:02:29.720
format a screenplay,
and before we knew it, we were filming.

00:02:29.720 --> 00:02:34.780
And it was a great education because the novel
is written

00:02:34.780 --> 00:02:42.510
from kind of a Holden Caulfield-esque first
person narrator voice.

00:02:42.510 --> 00:02:46.920
Gilbert's very angry and he exaggerates everything.

00:02:46.920 --> 00:02:50.930
He's quite unreliable, and Lasse said, "Look,
when we make the film,

00:02:50.930 --> 00:02:56.170
you can't make it in the tone of the book
because then we'll be making fun of everyone,

00:02:56.170 --> 00:02:59.150
and I can't, I just can't make fun of these
people."

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:03.630
And so that was probably the most--well first
of all learning

00:03:03.630 --> 00:03:11.140
how to to tell the story visually, and in
the cuts,

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:14.590
and with the fewest words possible was one
of the challenges.

00:03:14.590 --> 00:03:19.420
And the other was this, this education in
tone

00:03:19.420 --> 00:03:29.090
and how to tell the story so it would--it
wouldn't be making fun of the people

00:03:29.090 --> 00:03:30.440
the way Gilbert was.

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:36.150
To go from the first person unreliable to
sort of a third person kind of experience.

00:03:36.150 --> 00:03:38.110
&gt;&gt;Claire: Mmm hmm.

00:03:38.110 --> 00:03:40.069
Cool, very cool.

00:03:40.069 --> 00:03:45.880
So next we're going to move on to your directorial,
feature directorial debut, Pieces of April.

00:03:45.880 --> 00:03:48.440
So let's roll that clip.

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:49.440
[Pause]

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:51.340
&gt;&gt;Peter: Thank you.

00:03:51.340 --> 00:03:52.340
[Applause]

00:03:52.340 --> 00:03:55.990
&gt;&gt;Claire: Patricia Clarkson is so good.

00:03:55.990 --> 00:03:56.990
[Laughs]

00:03:56.990 --> 00:03:59.340
&gt;&gt;Peter: She's so good, we actually shot that
