00:43:56.009 --> 00:43:57.009
[Laughter]

00:43:57.009 --> 00:43:58.009
&gt;&gt; male #1: Thanks.

00:43:58.009 --> 00:43:59.009
&gt;&gt;Peter: So.

00:43:59.009 --> 00:44:00.009
Great question.

00:44:00.009 --> 00:44:04.019
&gt;&gt; male #2: So, looking at the film itself,
I thought it was amazing

00:44:04.019 --> 00:44:07.249
and my mind like raced back to like classics
of children's lit,

00:44:07.249 --> 00:44:10.599
things like Bridge to Terabithia, like Mary
Poppins.

00:44:10.599 --> 00:44:13.819
Was that like in your mind when you were working
with the screenplay,

00:44:13.819 --> 00:44:18.559
or how did you capture that sort of feeling
from children's lit in the film?

00:44:18.559 --> 00:44:25.309
&gt;&gt;Peter: True story, and I'm hesitant to say
this because I would in no way even

00:44:25.309 --> 00:44:28.099
suggest that Timothy Green is a classic.

00:44:28.099 --> 00:44:31.079
That's not for me to determine, or you even.

00:44:31.079 --> 00:44:36.900
Time determines what's a classic, but I very
much woke up one night

00:44:36.900 --> 00:44:42.320
in my home having had a dream where I was
directing and it was a bigger movie than I

00:44:42.320 --> 00:44:46.420
ever directed
and my wife said,"Why are you up?" and I said,

00:44:46.420 --> 00:44:48.410
"I want to make a classic."

00:44:48.410 --> 00:44:53.510
And she said,"What do you mean?" and I said,
"You know E.T., Wizard of Oz, It's a Wonderful

00:44:53.510 --> 00:44:56.650
Life,
one of those movies,"and this is really probably

00:44:56.650 --> 00:45:00.319
what I meant," One of those movies that you
watch and re-watch,

00:45:00.319 --> 00:45:03.230
you go back to time and time again.

00:45:03.230 --> 00:45:05.290
That's what I want to do."

00:45:05.290 --> 00:45:07.880
She said,"That's great," and then she went
back to bed.

00:45:07.880 --> 00:45:10.760
And I was still there,
and she said, "Why aren't you going back to

00:45:10.760 --> 00:45:11.760
bed?"

00:45:11.760 --> 00:45:12.819
And I said, "Well , there's a problem, I donât'
really come up with

00:45:12.819 --> 00:45:14.269
those ideas."

00:45:14.269 --> 00:45:16.400
Because I don't.

00:45:16.400 --> 00:45:19.470
Because each of those stories has a magical
element to it.

00:45:19.470 --> 00:45:24.289
Couple days later, I met the then president
of Disney for breakfast, he said, "Come home.

00:45:24.289 --> 00:45:25.289
Come back to Disney."

00:45:25.289 --> 00:45:28.819
I said, "That's great, but I don't really
have an idea.

00:45:28.819 --> 00:45:31.740
The things I'm writing right now are a bit
dirty, a bit

00:45:31.740 --> 00:45:34.019
inappropriate, and I just don't have a Disney
